FAQ
Can this skill write medical advice?
No. It can write general educational health and wellness content with appropriate caveats, but it must not diagnose, prescribe, or replace professional medical care.
Can it cite sources?
Yes, when sources are actually checked. If sources are not checked, it should provide a source plan and mark claims that need verification.
Can it write supplement content?
Yes, with extra caution. It should avoid disease treatment claims, flag interaction concerns, use precise evidence wording, and recommend expert review when appropriate.
Can it create calls to action?
Yes. CTAs should be responsible and scope-aware, such as inviting readers to learn more, save a checklist, or speak with a qualified professional.
Who is it for?
Health bloggers, wellness brands, coaches, newsletter writers, agencies, and editorial teams.
